-- REGRESSION GUARD (#712, S0): a USER constructor named `Cons`/`Nil` (the names the
-- built-in list syntax canonicalises to) among >=3 ctors must take its DECLARATION-
-- ORDER ordinal, NOT the built-in list synthetic ordinal (Cons=0/Nil=1).  The WasmGC
-- backend's `ctorOrdinal` used to short-circuit on the ctor NAME before consulting the
-- ctor table, so `data T = Extra | Cons Int T | Nil` gave the user `Cons` ordinal 0 —
-- COLLIDING with `Extra` (legitimately 0) — and wasm `br_table` silently sent a `Cons`
-- value to `Extra`'s arm.  eval + native (table/declaration-order) were always correct;
-- the fix makes wasm agree.  This is the S0 that #712's dup-type-id fix would otherwise
-- have UNMASKED (pre-#712 such a program failed to build on wasm at all).
data T = Extra | Cons Int T | Nil

tagT t = match t
  Extra => 100
  Cons _ _ => 200
  Nil => 300

main = (tagT Extra, tagT (Cons 5 (Cons 6 Nil)), tagT Nil)
